05369nam a22008415i 9789633866139DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97896338661397 a10.1515/97896338661392doi  a(DE-B1597)637792  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aGN21.H7bB73 2023 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a301.092aB223/eng/202303291 aBrandon, Mark A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Perils of Race-Thinking :bA Portrait of Aleš Hrdlička /cMark A. Brandon. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCEU Press Studies in the History of Medicine ;v1400tFrontmatter -- tTABLE OF CONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tChapter I What are the Czechoslovaks Racially? -- tChapter II “Public Opinion is a Powerful Weapon” -- tChapter III The Secret History of the Hrdlička Museum of Man -- tChapter IV The Last Great Reserve of the White Race -- tChapter V Race Divination -- tChapter VI How the Czechs Became White -- tChapter VII Eugenics -- tChapter VIII The Faith of Aleš Hrdlička -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEugenics and scientific racism are experiencing a resurgence, and only by understanding the work of Aleš Hrdlička and others will we be able to combat them. In our age of rapid advances of genetic studies within historical research the racial science of the early twentieth century is treated with contempt. This book is about an arch figure of that period: Aleš Hrdlička served as Curator of Physical Anthropology at the prestigious Smithsonian Institution from 1910 to 1941. Although his output is today considered pseudoscience, he adhered to the standards of his profession of his age. During World War I, Hrdlička collaborated with propagandists to convince the American public to support the Czechoslovak cause. In 1938, he pleaded publicly against the German annexation of the Sudeten region. Although a prolific author, he refused to change his difficult name, which signaled his ardent commitment to Czech identity. In his view, Germans and Czechs were locked in a millennial struggle that was racial, and the Slavs were a eugenic bastion against the “rising tide of color.” On the global stage, Hrdlička publicized Soviet Union as the citadel of Slavic whiteness. By placing Czech nationalism at the center of the Czech-American scholar’s mental map, this book contributes to the research on the development of Western racial thinking.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAnthropologistszCzech RepubliczBohemiavBiography. 0aAnthropologistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aEugenicsxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhysical anthropologyxHistoryy20th century. 0aScientific racismxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aCzechoslovakia.  aHistory of science.  ahistory of anthropology.  anationalism.  arace.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2023z978311079759608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Comm 2023 Englishz978311131910008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Communication 2023z9783111318141oZDB-23-SEW0 cprintz978963386612240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789633866139?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633866139423Coveruhttp